content:
Send Images and Files in Messaging Sessions

Sometimes, only a picture will do. Resolve customer inquiries faster by sending images and files during Service Cloud messaging sessions.

This article applies to: Messaging for In-App, Messaging for Web, standard and enhanced WhatsApp, standard and enhanced Facebook Messenger, standard and enhanced SMS, enhanced Apple Messages for Business, and Bring Your Own Channel

To send images and files, click the paperclip icon in the messaging window. Select the image or file that you want to send. If your file is a public link, optionally create an expiration date for it.

Supported file types and maximum attachment size vary depending on the channel type:

* Messaging for In-App and Web: 5 MB, .pdf, .png, .jpeg, .jpg, .bmp, .tiff, .gif
* WhatsApp (Standard): 5 MB, .jpg, .jpeg, .png, .pdf, .gif
* WhatsApp (Enhanced): varies by file type, see Compare Standard and Enhanced WhatsApp Channel Capabilities
* Facebook Messenger (Standard): 25 MB, .jpg, .jpeg, .png, .gif
* Facebook Messenger (Enhanced): 25 MB, .jpg, .jpeg png, .bmp, .tiff, .webp, .txt, .pdf, .psd, .rtf, .xls, .xml, .exe, .zip, .mp3, .mov, .mp4, .3gp, .gif
* Apple Messages for Business (Enhanced): 100 MB, .png, .jpg, .jpeg, .bmp, .tiff, .txt, .pdf, .psd, .rtf, .xls, .xlsx, .doc, .docx, .ppt, .json, .pptx, .pps, .ppsx, .csv, .xml, .pkpass, .ics, .exe, .zip, .usdz, .mp3, .caf, .mov, .mp4, .3gp, .gif
* Partner Messaging: 25 MB, .png, .jpg, .jpeg, .bmp, .tiff, .gif, .txt, .pdf, .psd, .rtf, .xls, .xlsx, .doc, .docx, .ppt, .pptx, .json, .pps, .ppsx, .csv, .xml, .mov, .mp4, .3gp, .3g2, .mpg, .mp3, .caf, .m4a, .exe, .zip, .ics, .pkpass, .usdz
* SMS long codes (Standard and enhanced): varies by carrier, see below
	+ AT&T: 1 MB, .jpg, .jpeg, .png, .gif
	+ T-Mobile: 1 MB, .jpg, .jpeg, .png, .gif
	+ Verizon: 1.2 MB, .jpg, .jpeg, .png, .gif
	+ Sprint: 2 MB, .jpg, .jpeg, .png, .gif
	+ US cellular: 500 KB, .jpg, .jpeg, .png, .gif
* SMS toll-free long codes (Standard and enhanced): 525 KB, .jpg, .jpeg, .png, .gif
title: Sending Images and Files in Service Cloud Messaging Sessions
